    fullDescription: "Just over the German border, two and a quarter hours north by direct train, Dresden makes a rewarding cross-border day trip and a fascinating contrast to Prague. Once the glittering baroque capital of Saxony and nicknamed the 'Florence on the Elbe', the city was devastated by Allied firebombing in February 1945, and its painstaking post-war and post-reunification reconstruction is a moving story of rebirth in its own right. The compact old town, an easy walk from the main station, packs in a cluster of magnificently restored landmarks: the domed Frauenkirche, rebuilt from its rubble and reconsecrated in 2005; the sprawling Zwinger palace with its ornate courtyards and galleries; the Semperoper opera house; the Royal Palace; and the Brühl's Terrace promenade along the Elbe, dubbed the 'Balcony of Europe'. World-class museums, including the Old Masters Picture Gallery (home to Raphael's Sistine Madonna) and the dazzling Green Vault treasury, reward those with more time. Remember it's a separate country, so carry your passport and some euros. For visitors keen to add a slice of Germany and some superb baroque architecture and art to their Czech trip, Dresden is a splendid, easily reached full-day excursion.",
